17 August 2022

### District Judge Sharmila Sripathy-Shanaz:

## Introduction

1       The Accused contested a charge for failing, without reasonable excuse, to provide a specimen of his urine sample within such time as required by Station Inspector Lim Sui Siong Aaron (“SI Aaron”), a police officer. This was an offence under s 31(2) of the Misuse of Drugs Act (Cap 185, 2008 Rev Ed) (“the MDA”), punishable under s 33A(2) of the same Act.

2       At the close of the trial, I found that the Prosecution had established its case beyond a reasonable doubt and convicted the Accused accordingly. By law, he was liable to a mandatory minimum term of 7 years’ imprisonment and caning of not less than 6 strokes. By virtue of his age however, the Accused could not be caned.[\[note: 1\]](#Ftn_1) I sentenced him to 7 years’ and 3 months’ imprisonment and declined to impose any imprisonment in lieu of caning.

3       Dissatisfied, the Accused has filed an appeal against his conviction and sentence. He is currently serving sentence.

## The Elements of the Offence

4       This judgment is broadly structured to address the key elements of an offence under s 31(2) of the MD, namely that:

> a.     a police officer holding the rank of sergeant and above, required the accused to provide a specimen of his urine for testing as he reasonably suspected that the accused had committed an offence of consumption of a controlled drug;

> b.     the accused failed to provide his urine specimen within such time as required by the said police officer; and

> c.     the accused did not have a reasonable excuse for failing to provide his urine specimen.

## Overview of the Parties’ Positions

5       In the present case, the Accused’s failure to provide a urine specimen was not in dispute. Instead, the key issue at trial was whether the Accused had a _reasonable excuse_ for this failure, and it was on this, that the parties differed.

6       The Prosecution asserted that the Accused had wilfully _refused_ to provide a sample of his urine despite being medically fit for urine testing. In contrast, the Accused’s principal assertion was that he had been _unable_ (as opposed to being _unwilling_) to provide a urine specimen at the material time as he was suffering from urinary retention due to his consumption of Tramadol (a prescribed medication) in the days preceding his arrest. Allied to this was the Accused’s contention that urinary retention is a known side effect of Tramadol consumption.

7       In addition to the above, the Accused also appeared to challenge the basis of his arrest on suspicion of having consumed controlled drugs.

8       Elements (a) and (c) (_supra_ at \[4\]) were thus the main issues in contention at trial. I examine each of these issues in due course, but turn first, to summarize the evidence led by the respective parties.

## The Prosecution’s Case

### The Accused’s Arrest

9       The police received a call at about 9.28 p.m. on 25 March 2019, reporting as follows:[\[note: 2\]](#Ftn_2)

> There is a man outside my neighbour’s house. He has been there for a while. He might be taking drugs. I am looking from my CCTV, I though (sic) I saw him lighting up and syringe (sic).

10     Sergeant Low Si Jia Amanda (“Sgt Low”) and Staff Sergeant Abu Hamid Bin Abu Shama (“SSgt Hamid”) were dispatched to investigate the report and arrived at the incident location situated within a Housing Development Board estate, to find the Accused lying in a sleeping position on the steps of an apartment along the common corridor.[\[note: 3\]](#Ftn_3) Concerned that he was injured or unwell, Sgt Low tapped the Accused’s shoulder to rouse him. After several attempts, the Accused awoke and was observed to be _“drowsy”_ and _“groggy”_. The arresting officers’ attempts to elicit information from the Accused were hampered by his inability to speak coherently and in full sentences. He presented with slurred speech as well as bloodshot eyes and was also unable to stand.[^4] Sgt Low’s observations were subsequently detailed in Exhibit P3 as follows:

![](data:image;base64,)

11     At about 10.05 p.m., the Accused was arrested on suspicion of having consumed a controlled drug and was conveyed to the Police Cantonment Complex (“PCC”) for investigations.[\[note: 5\]](#Ftn_5) The Accused did not, during his interactions with the arresting officers, complain of feeling unwell nor inform them that he had consumed medication.[^6] No medication (Tramadol or otherwise) was found on the Accused during either of the two searches conducted on him at the scene of arrest and prior to handing him to lock-up officers in PCC.[^7]

### The Formal Request for a Specimen of Urine

12     At about 11.25 p.m., whilst in PCC lock-up, SI Aaron administered a warning to the Accused, requiring him to provide a urine specimen for testing and informing him of the consequences of failing to do so. This marked the beginning of the formal request for a specimen of the Accused’s urine. The Accused ignored the warning and refused to provide a urine specimen,[\[note: 8\]](#Ftn_8) informing SI Aaron that he would not do so until he was allowed to see his Investigation Officer, one Mr Razif (“IO Razif”), to whom he had been reporting for routine urine testing.[^9] This exchange was recorded in Exhibit P10 as follows:

![](data:image;base64,)

### The Attempts to Procure a Urine Specimen

13     Between 11.26 p.m. on 25 March 2019 and 1.25 a.m. on 26 March 2019, each of SI Aaron’s requests for the Accused to provide a urine specimen at 30-minute intervals, went unheeded as he maintained that he would not comply until permitted to see IO Razif.[\[note: 10\]](#Ftn_10) Each request for a urine sample was accompanied by an offer of water and while the Accused drank some cups of water,[^11] he refused others.[^12] At no juncture, throughout his interactions with SI Aaron, did the Accused complain of feeling unwell.[^13] He also made no mention of having consumed any medication prior to his arrest.[^14]

14     At about 1.30 a.m., the Accused was transferred to a padded cell as he was shouting and was assessed to be uncooperative.[\[note: 15\]](#Ftn_15)

15     Between 2.00 a.m. and 6.30 a.m. on 26 March 2019, then Senior Station Inspector Mohamed Jahankeer (“SSI Jahankeer”) continued to offer the Accused a cup of water at 30-minute intervals and request that he provide a urine specimen. Again, while the Accused consumed some cups of water,[\[note: 16\]](#Ftn_16) he rejected others.[^17] On each occasion, the Accused refused, without explanation, to provide his urine specimen.[^18]

21     Dr Tan testified that while there was a _“theoretical risk of urine retention”_ after Tramadol consumption, he had never encountered one in his years of practise.[\[note: 30\]](#Ftn_30) Dr Tan also testified that urinary retention _“would not go away without any intervention”_ as _“the body is unlikely to pass urine on its own without intervention”_ and at that stage, _“the only treatment is to put a catheter”_.[^31]

#### Evidence of Dr Rahalkar Kshitij (“Dr Rahalkar”)

22     At about 3.27 p.m. on 26 March 2019, the Accused was re-conveyed to SGH and examined by Dr Rahalkar in the Emergency Department after complaining of a headache, giddiness, chest pain, cough, runny nose, constipation and an episode of syncope.[\[note: 32\]](#Ftn_32) The Accused’s vital signs were stable, no neurological deficits were observed and examination of his abdomen revealed it was _“soft and non-tender”_,[^33]_“unremarkable”_ and _“normal”_.[^34] Blood investigations showed a normal renal panel which indicated that the Accused’s kidney function was _“normal”_ and _“not impaired”_.[^35]

23     The Accused did not raise any urinary complaints to Dr Rahalkar.[\[note: 36\]](#Ftn_36)

#### Evidence of Dr Ling Hua Chan (“Dr Ling”)

24     Subsequent to Dr Rahalkar’s examination, the Accused was admitted to the Department of Internal Medicine at SGH for further evaluation of his self-reported chest pain and headache. When Dr Ling assessed the Accused at about 1.46 a.m. on 27 March 2019, his vital signs were normal and upon physical examination, his stomach was noted to be soft and non-tender with no signs of pain or guarding.[\[note: 37\]](#Ftn_37)

25     The Accused did not complain of any urinary problems to Dr Ling.[\[note: 38\]](#Ftn_38)

#### The Accused’s Medical Examination Prior to His Arrest

32     Dr Cheong Hong Fai (“Dr Cheong”) assessed the Accused at the Emergency Department of Ng Teng Fong General Hospital on 21 March 2019 (four days prior to his arrest) for a headache and cough. The Accused did not raise any urinary complaints to Dr Cheong during this consultation.[\[note: 44\]](#Ftn_44) Various medications, including Tramadol, were prescribed to the Accused following this consultation. Outpatient sick leave from 21 March 2019 to 25 March 2019 was granted at the Accused’s request despite Dr Cheong’s assessment that the Accused was well and _“\[did\] not require 4 days of MC”_.[^45]

33     Dr Cheong testified that nausea and vomiting are common side effects of Tramadol consumption and he had not, in all his years of practice, seen anyone with urinary retention after consuming Tramadol.[\[note: 46\]](#Ftn_46)

34     Dr Wang Jiali, who had prepared the medical report (Exhibit P9) on Dr Cheong’s behalf, had stated that:

![](data:image;base64,)

35     In Court, Dr Wang explained that ‘susceptible hosts’ were elderly patients above 65 years of age who had impaired mobility (such as those who were chairbound or bedbound) and other concurrent medical conditions and were thus _“more vulnerable to the side effects of tramadol”_. Dr Wang testified that urinary retention caused by Tramadol consumption was _“uncommon”_ and explained that in her experience, urinary retention in patients was multifactorial and not owing solely to Tramadol consumption.[\[note: 47\]](#Ftn_47)

36     Responding to a question about how a patient who had been unable to urinate for 48 hours would present, Dr Wang explained that such a patient would be in _“a lot of pain and discomfort over \[their\] suprapubic region”.__[\[note: 48\]](#Ftn_48)_

### Other Salient Evidence

37     The evidence of Investigation Officer Vinod s/o Pannerchilvam (“IO Vinod”) was salient in the following aspects:

> a.     there were no records of the Accused having undergone catheterization at TTSH;[\[note: 49\]](#Ftn_49)

> b.     if the Accused had medication with him at the time of his arrest, this would have been relevant to investigations and a seizure would have been made. The seized exhibit would then have been referred to IO Vinod. In the present case, no medication (Tramadol or otherwise) was seized from the Accused upon his arrest;[\[note: 50\]](#Ftn_50)

> c.     the Accused was released on police bail sometime between 11.30 p.m. on 26 March 2019 and just past midnight on 27 March 2019;[\[note: 51\]](#Ftn_51) and

> d.     on 30 September 2014, the Accused had been convicted of consumption of a specified drug and being liable for punishment under s 33A(1) of the MDA, was sentenced to 5 years’ imprisonment with 3 strokes of the cane. A memorandum of certified previous convictions, Exhibit P24, was tendered in support of this.

This phrase, ‘tak nak’ was translated to _‘refuse’_ in English.[\[note: 52\]](#Ftn_52) According to SSgt Aldi, the Accused did not provide any reason for refusing these opportunities and simply stated that _“he doesn’t want to.”_[^53]

## The Defence’s Case

42     The Accused testified and called his wife, Madam Sumiyati Binte Md Saad (“Mdm Sumiyati”), to give evidence on his behalf.

### The Accused’s Evidence

43     The Accused’s evidence, as gleaned from his testimony, is summarized below.

44     The Accused left home following an argument with his wife on 25 March 2019 and had intended to spend the night at his cousin’s home. He was smoking and waiting outside his cousin’s apartment when the arresting officers approached him and asked what he was doing there. The Accused told the officers that he was waiting for his cousin to return home. His attempts to call his cousin at the arresting officers’ behest, were unsuccessful _“because the prepaid \[had\] finished”_. The Accused was also unable to furnish another phone number as he did not have it. He then asked the officers to call another number but that call similarly did not go through.[\[note: 57\]](#Ftn_57)

45     At the time of his arrest, the Accused claimed to have had his medication (which included Tramadol), cigarettes and a lighter with him. He told the arresting officers that he was unwell and that he had medication with him. He also alleged that he had told the arresting officers that he had consumed Tramadol. [\[note: 58\]](#Ftn_58) At the tail end of his testimony, the Accused also claimed to have informed the police upon arrest, that he had difficulties urinating.[^59]

46     At PCC, the Accused informed an unidentified officer that he was unwell and that he had medication with him.[\[note: 60\]](#Ftn_60) According to the Accused, these medications were only returned to him when he was subsequently released on bail.[^61]

47     The Accused testified that he was _unable_ to comply with requests for a specimen of his urine despite drinking the water provided to him and attempting to urinate. He was subsequently conveyed to the hospital where he told the doctor that he had a headache, migraine and backpain. The doctor told him there was nothing wrong with him and told him to return home. Thereafter, the Accused was escorted back to the lock-up[\[note: 62\]](#Ftn_62) where he continued consuming the water provided to him and tried to provide a urine specimen but was still unable to do so. He recounted feeling stressed and asked himself why he could not urinate. As he was light-headed and felt that he was going to faint, he was conveyed back to SGH. [^63]

48     At SGH, the Accused was placed on a drip as his blood pressure was low. When he asked an unidentified doctor why he could not urinate, the doctor told him that they would _“settle one-by-one first.”_ When he was subsequently examined by a team of doctors and told them _“I cannot pass motion, I cannot pass urine \[,\] they said “don’t worry, \[we\] will try to find something.”_[\[note: 64\]](#Ftn_64) According to the Accused, he also _“did not urine anywhere”_ whilst in the hospital.[^65] He disputed the information in the intake/output chart (Exhibit P17) and claimed not to have challenged Dr Swee’s evidence on this issue as he was inexperienced in trial matters.[^66]

49     The Accused explained that he had refused catheterization as he did not want to exacerbate the pain he was already in. He had asked SSgt Aldi if he could provide a hair, saliva or blood sample but the latter was disinterested and merely asked the Accused to sign his statement.[\[note: 67\]](#Ftn_67) During cross-examination, the Accused denied telling Dr Tan that he had been previously catheterized at TTSH.[^68]

50     According to the Accused, he had started consuming Tramadol on 21 March 2019, after it had been prescribed to him by Dr Cheong.[\[note: 69\]](#Ftn_69) Between 21 March and 25 March 2019, the Accused claimed to have taken four pills of Tramadol, daily.[^70] During cross-examination, the Accused testified that he had no urinary problems prior to his arrest and had in fact, been reporting for regular urine testing. However, the Accused subsequently testified that he was unable to urinate and pass motion from as early as 22 March 2019 and this persisted on 24 and 25 March 2019.[^71] He omitted telling doctors that his urinary difficulties had begun on 24 March 2019 as he _“thought it was nothing.”_[^72] He further asserted that he only realized that Tramadol consumption could cause urinary retention when he received Dr Wang’s medical report sometime before the trial commenced in September 2021.[^73]

### The Evidence of Mdm Sumiyati

51     Mdm Sumiyati is the Accused’s wife. She testified that the Accused had been consuming Tramadol since his accident sometime in 2010 or 2011. The Accused was _“okay”_ and would be able to work, help with household chores and play with his grandchildren when he took Tramadol.[\[note: 74\]](#Ftn_74)

52     According to Mdm Sumiyati, the Accused had consumed two tablets of Tramadol at about 11.00 a.m. on 25 March 2019. When he wanted to consume a second dose of the medication at about 2.00 p.m., she made _“noise”_ and _“asked him why do you want to eat the medications.”_ Due to their argument, the Accused left the house with his medication. She was unaware of where he went.[\[note: 75\]](#Ftn_75)

53     Mdm Sumiyati testified that she would be beside the Accused whenever he consumed his medication. As it was only the two of them and she was not working, Mdm Sumiyati even claimed that _“when he went to urine, I will also be with him”_.[\[note: 76\]](#Ftn_76)

## The Court’s Findings

54     I turn now to examine, _in seriatim_, the issues in dispute (_supra_ at \[4\] and \[8\]).

### Finding On Issue 1: There was Probable Cause for the Accused’s Arrest and the Request for a Urine Specimen

55     I begin by considering the evidence in relation to the first issue – that is, whether there was basis for the Accused’s arrest on suspicion of having consumed a controlled drug. For the reasons that follow, I found that there was ample basis for the arrest.

56     Though no drug related paraphernalia was found on the Accused when he was searched by Sgt Low and SSSgt Abu Hamid, the officers’ observations led them to suspect that he was under the influence of drugs. In this regard, it would be recalled that Sgt Low had testified that the Accused was lying on the ground in front of an apartment when she arrived at the scene. Upon being roused, the Accused was drowsy, incoherent, had slurred speech and was unable to stand. Sgt Low’s observations were duly recorded in Exhibit P3, the full incident report she had lodged subsequent to the Accused’s arrest (_supra_ at \[10\]). Sgt Low’s evidence was further corroborated by SSSgt Abu Hamid who similarly observed that the Accused was groggy, unable to sit or stand unassisted, unable to communicate in full sentences and, additionally, had bloodshot eyes.

57     While the Accused appeared to accept that he was drowsy and ‘giddy’ (to use his own words),[\[note: 77\]](#Ftn_77) he attributed this to the fact that he was unwell and suffering the side-effects of Tramadol consumption. In my assessment, this assertion did not withstand scrutiny in light of Sgt Low’s and SSSgt Abu Hamid’s evidence that the Accused had not, throughout their interactions with him, complained of feeling unwell nor alluded to having consumed any medication. Contrary to his claims, the Accused was also not found in possession of any medication, Tramadol or otherwise, during either of the _two_ searches conducted on him by the arresting officers at the scene of arrest and at the PCC lock-up – a fact that IO Vinod similarly attested to (_supra_ at \[37b\]).

58     Even _if_, giving the Accused the benefit of doubt, I did accept that he had consumed Tramadol prior to his arrest, I did not accept that his demeanour at the time of his arrest was attributable to the medication’s side effects. In this regard, I noted Mdm Sumiyati’s _unchallenged_ evidence that the Accused was _“okay”_ whenever he consumed Tramadol. Her evidence in fact revealed that the Accused was able to work, help with household chores and play with his grandchildren after medicating with Tramadol (_supra_ at \[51\]). In other words, rather than incapacitating his physical or mental faculties, Tramadol enabled the Accused to function effectively. The Accused’s assertion to the contrary at trial, was thus squarely contradicted by his own wife.

59     To my mind, there was no real question of any lack of probable cause. The first information report coupled with the arresting officers own observations of the Accused, provided basis for a reasonable suspicion that he had committed an offence under s 8(b) of the MDA. His arrest and the subsequent requests by SI Aaron for the Accused to provide a specimen of his urine for testing, were thus unassailable.

### Finding On Issue 2: The Accused Failed to Provide a Urine Specimen

60     The second issue, _viz._ whether the Accused had failed to provide his urine specimen within such time as required by SI Aaron, was not in dispute. To this end, Exhibits P10 and P22 document attempts to procure the Accused’s urine specimen on no less than 15 occasions between 11.25 p.m. on 25 March 2019 and 6.30 a.m. on 26 March 2019. It was also not in dispute that the Accused was warned, and was thus aware, of the consequences of his failure to comply with these requests (_supra_ at \[12\]).

### Finding On Issue 3: The Accused Had No Reasonable Excuse for Failing to Provide His Urine Specimen

61     In light of the above, it only remained for the Court to consider if the Accused was suffering from urinary retention at the material time and thus had a reasonable excuse for failing to provide his urine specimen. Having assiduously assessed the parties’ respective cases, I found that the objective evidence before the Court simply did not cohere with such a finding. I explain.

#### The medical evidence showed that the Accused was not suffering from urinary retention

62     Foremost, the Accused’s contention that he was incapable of providing his urine specimen, was unequivocally rebutted by the medical evidence.

63     It would be useful to begin the analysis by considering the characteristics and symptoms of urinary retention. It was undisputed that the condition, which occurs when a patient continues to produce urine but is unable to urinate,[\[note: 78\]](#Ftn_78) results in a significantly distended bladder which is palpable by the examining doctor. A patient in urinary retention would be in significant distress, feel very uncomfortable and require urinary catheterization to relieve the pressure he experiences (_supra_ at \[30\]).

64     Against this backdrop, I make the following observations:

> a.     Dr Kang testified that the “_possible_ palpable bladder” noted on examination of the Accused’s abdomen was _inconclusive_ and required referral to the hospital for confirmation with an ultrasound and further assessment. Dr Kang also testified that the suprapubic tenderness elicited on examination, was self-reported by the Accused (_supra_ at \[17\]);

> b.     Dr Tan who, subsequent to Dr Kang’s referral, examined the Accused, testified that he was _“not in distress”_ and did not have a palpable bladder. A bedside ultrasound performed on the Accused also did not disclose a distended bladder and blood test results were _“normal”_. Having excluded pre-renal, renal and post-renal causes for the purported inability to urinate, and there being no _“urological deficit”_ or _“pathological disorder”_ preventing him from providing a urine specimen, Dr Tan certified that the Accused was fit for urine testing (_supra_ at \[19\]);

> c.     Dr Rahalkar testified that the Accused did not have any urinary complaints nor complain of abdominal pain. Examination of the Accused’s abdomen was _“unremarkable or normal”_ and noted to be _“soft and non-tender”_. His renal panel was likewise normal, indicating normal kidney function (_supra_ at \[22\]);

> d.     Dr Ling observed that the Accused’s abdomen was _“soft and non-tender”_ and no _“guarding”_ or pain was present upon palpation (_supra_ at \[24\]); and

> e.     Dr Swee testified that the Accused was never deemed unfit to provide a urine specimen as none of the conditions he was being treated for (self-reported atypical chest pain, self-reported presyncope and microcytic anaemia) would result in an inability to provide a urine sample and there was no evidence that he was retaining urine and unable to urinate (_supra_ at \[26\] and \[27\]).

65     For completeness, I pause to address the Accused’s assertion that he was suffering from urinary retention due to his consumption of Tramadol. The evidence disclosed that while urinary retention is a _possible_ side effect of Tramadol consumption, it is an _“infrequent”_ and _“uncommon”_ consequence that afflicts _less than_ 5% of “susceptible hosts” (i.e., those above 65 years of age who have impaired mobility and concurrent medical conditions); _supra_ at \[30\] and \[35\]. Even _if_ I did accept that the Accused had consumed Tramadol prior to his arrest (an assertion which was itself, for the reasons canvassed at \[74\] to \[75\] below, problematic), whether it triggered urinary retention in the present case, remained very much a question of fact.

66     Ultimately, on the facts before me, the medical evidence indisputably disclosed not only that the Accused was medically fit to provide a urine specimen, but also that he did not (save for the _single_ self-reported complaint of suprapubic pain to Dr Kang which never again resurfaced) present with _any_ of the signs and symptoms (distilled at \[63\] above) suggestive of urinary retention. Thus viewed, the facts simply did not support the proposition that the Accused was in urinary retention and incapable of urinating at the material time.

#### The Accused was clearly capable of urinating

67     Second, fortifying the aforesaid finding was the fact that the Accused had urinated _twice_, unassisted, several hours after being released on bail. Exhibit P17, charted by nurses during the Accused’s inpatient observation at SGH, reveals that these uninhibited acts of urination had occurred at 7.56 a.m. and 12.30 p.m. on 27 March 2019 – mere _hours_ after his release on bail at around midnight.

68     While the Accused subsequently challenged the accuracy of Exhibit P17 and claimed that he _“did not urinate anywhere”_, I remained unpersuaded by his disavowal of the objective medical records given the belatedness of the assertion (which arose only when he was under cross-examination)[\[note: 79\]](#Ftn_79)_and_ the absence of a cogent explanation for how and why the nurses would have incorrectly ascribed these acts to him.

#### The Defence was undermined by inconsistencies in the Accused’s claims

69     Third, I found the cogency of the defence significantly undermined by the inconsistent narratives proffered by the Accused for his failure to provide a urine sample at the material time. In this connection, I noted that:

> a.     the Accused did not complain to SI Aaron or SSI Jahankeer of _any_ urinary problems during their many interactions with him. Instead, he repeatedly _refused_ to comply with SI Aaron’s request for a urine specimen until he was permitted to see one IO Razif. Thereafter, he repeatedly _refused_ SSI Jahankeer’s requests for a urine specimen with nary a reason provided; and

> b.     the Accused also did not, after being informed by Dr Tan that there was nothing inhibiting his ability to urinate, complain of _any_ urinary problems or abdominal discomfort to any of the three doctors who had subsequently attended to him at SGH between 3.27 p.m. on 26 March 2019 and 9.00 a.m. on 27 March 2019. Instead, he reported a smorgasbord of other wholly unconnected symptoms ranging from a migraine, syncope, a cough and a runny nose, to back pain and chest pain. No cogent explanation for this glaring failure to report to these doctors, the _purportedly persisting_ urinary difficulties he was experiencing throughout his time in custody, was forthcoming.

70     In fact, I was mindful that based on the evidence of the Prosecution witnesses, the Accused’s _only_ urinary complaints on 26 March 2019, were to Dr Kang (when he reported being _“unable to pass urine for 3 hours”_) and Dr Tan (who had to further investigate this claim). Even then, in assessing the veracity of these urinary complaints, several points bear highlighting:

> a.     Exhibit P18 shows that the initial complaint of urinary trouble only emerged because the Accused had complained of a migraine and SI Chan had of his _own volition_, upon referring him to Dr Kang, simultaneously sought an assessment of the Accused’s fitness to provide a urine specimen (_supra_ at \[16\]). In other words, the reason for the referral to Dr Kang stemmed from the Accused’s complaint of a migraine and _not_ owing to any urinary complaint he had made to the police officers in lock-up, when asked to provide his urine sample; and

> b.     pertinently, the _duration_ of the Accused’s purported urinary problem morphed in the course of his own testimony in Court. Under cross-examination the Accused had testified that he was able to urinate without problem up until his arrest on 25 March 2019. He subsequently vacillated during re-examination, and in response to clarifications sought by this Court, alleged that his urinary travails had in fact begun as early as 22 March 2019 (_supra_ at \[50\]). The latter was in fact squarely contradicted by Mdm Sumiyati’s evidence that her husband was _“okay”_ after consuming Tramadol. Further, though Mdm Sumiyati would have been expected to know if her husband had experienced any urinary impairment in the days prior to his arrest, since she so readily claimed to have been with him whenever he urinated (_supra_ at \[53\]), no such evidence from her was forthcoming.

71     In my assessment, these material contradictions and glaring omissions in the Defence case, undermined the veracity of the Accused’s claims and reinforced the finding that nothing (save for an obdurate refusal to comply) had impeded his ability to provide a urine specimen at the material time.

#### There were other untenable aspects of the Defence case

72     Fourth, there were aspects of the Defence’s case which were inherently incredible, and which coalesced to cast significant doubt on the underlying claims.

73     Chief amongst these was the Accused’s assertion that his urinary problems emerged only on the day of arrest (or several days before, depending on which version he preferred to rely on), despite a purported nearly decade long history of Tramadol consumption, only to _conveniently_ dissipate without medical treatment/intervention within _hours_ of his release on bail; his overall malaise abating to the extent that he was content to leave the hospital without the permission or knowledge of medical personnel.

74     The Accused’s contention that he had consumed Tramadol in the days preceding his arrest, was another aspect of the Defence case that was highly suspect. I was cognizant of the fact that there was no mention of this important detail in the Accused’s statement (Exhibit P4), which he accepted had been given voluntarily and which SSgt Aldi had testified to having recorded accurately, despite being asked to account for any medication (traditional or otherwise) that he had consumed. The testimonies of the various Prosecution witnesses (whose evidence was consistent and I had no reason to doubt) also disclosed that there was similarly no mention of this fact to the arresting officers, lock-up officers or any of the five doctors who had examined the Accused. Further, contrary to his protestations, no Tramadol was found on the Accused during his arrest.

75     Quite apart from the above, the Accused’s own evidence as to his alleged Tramadol consumption was fraught with inconsistencies. To name a few; whereas the Accused had testified to having consumed Tramadol from 21 March 2019, Mdm Sumiyati claimed that he had been doing so since 2010 or 2011. As observed above, Mdm Sumiyati’s evidence that the Accused was _“okay”_ and able to function normally after consuming Tramadol, was also at odds with his claim that it resulted in urinary retention, drowsiness and giddiness. These omissions and inconsistencies suggested that the Accused’s assertion that he had consumed Tramadol in the days preceding his arrest, was but an afterthought.

76     Nonetheless, even _if_ I did accept the Accused’s claim that he had consumed four, 50 milligram tablets of Tramadol daily (i.e., 200 milligrams daily) between 21 March 2019 and 25 March 2019, it was Dr Wang’s _unchallenged_ evidence that this was still within the recommended _“safety dosage range”_.[\[note: 80\]](#Ftn_80) While there is no doubt a remote risk of urinary retention in an individual who consumes Tramadol, we return to the primary question in _this_ case, _viz._ whether the Accused was indeed suffering from urinary retention at the material time. I have already provided my findings on this issue (_supra_ at \[62\] to \[68\]). In sum, the objective evidence showed that at all material times, the Accused was not suffering from urinary retention and was medically fit to provide a urine specimen. There was thus no reasonable excuse, medical or otherwise, for his failure to do so.

#### The Accused refused to provide his urine sample via catheterization

77     Finally, even _if_ (in spite of the foregoing analysis) I did accept that the Accused was suffering from urinary retention which impeded his ability to urinate, I could not disregard the fact that his urine specimen could nonetheless have been provided with the aid of a urinary catheter. This option of catheterization was in fact offered to the Accused _twice_ but declined each time.

78     On the first occasion, Dr Tan had offered catheterization to test the Accused’s enthusiasm for pain relief as significant distress being a symptom of urinary retention, Dr Tan had wanted to assess _“how urgent or how enthusiastic”_ the Accused was for relief. Notably, the Accused refused the offer on the premise that he had undergone the procedure in Tan Tock Seng Hospital previously and found it to be very painful. I noted however, Dr Tan’s evidence that a perusal of the Accused’s national health records did not disclose any previous record of catheterization having been performed on him. This was similarly corroborated by IO Vinod whose checks with Tan Tock Seng Hospital yielded the same result. While the Accused did not dispute Dr Tan’s and IO Vinod’s evidence when they were testifying, he subsequently denied making any such statement to Dr Tan when cross-examined by the Prosecution. I regarded this as no more than a feeble attempt by the Accused to distance himself from damning evidence which revealed that he had lied to Dr Tan, knowing that it was demonstrative of an intent to frustrate _all_ attempts to procure a urine sample from him. I should add that I saw no reason to disbelief Dr Tan’s evidence about what the Accused had said to him, as he has no vested interest in these criminal proceedings.

79     A second opportunity for urinary catheterization presented itself during the recording of the Accused’s statement between 10.15 p.m. and 11.00 p.m. on 26 March 2019. This offer by SSgt Aldi was similarly refused by the Accused, albeit without any explanation. In my judgment, the Accused’s repeated rejection of _two_ opportunities to provide his urine specimen via catheterization, betrayed an intransigent and brazen defiance of the urine procurement process which he was clearly intent on frustrating by any means possible.

## The Finding of Guilt

80     Given that the Accused had no medical impediment inhibiting the production and excretion of urine, I found that he had no reasonable excuse for failing to provide a specimen of his urine. Indeed, the circumstances showed that the Accused had wilfully refused to provide a urine sample. I thus convicted him on the charge.

## Sentencing

81     The prescribed punishment for the offence of failing to provide a urine sample in the present case, was a mandatory minimum of seven years’ imprisonment and caning.

82     The Accused was not a first offender. Between 1996 and 2014, he served several terms of imprisonment for drug offences. These convictions and the sentences imposed, are set out in the following table:

### The Parties’ Positions

83     The Prosecution submitted that an uplift of six months’ imprisonment to the mandatory minimum sentence was warranted as the Accused had claimed trial despite the absence of a reasonable defence.[\[note: 81\]](#Ftn_81) No imprisonment in lieu of the mandatory caning was sought.

84     The Accused urged the Court to impose a sentence of no more than three years’ imprisonment. He maintained this submission despite being informed that the sentence he sought was not one that could be lawfully imposed as he had been convicted of an offence which carried a prescribed _minimum_ sentence of seven years’ imprisonment.[\[note: 82\]](#Ftn_82)

### The Sentence Imposed

85     I agreed with the Prosecution’s submission that the Accused had claimed trial despite overwhelming medical evidence that rendered his defence patently untenable. The resulting trial spanned six days[\[note: 83\]](#Ftn_83) and necessitated the calling of 15 Prosecution witnesses.

86     It is a settled principle of sentencing that a plea of guilt evincing true remorse and contrition, is a mitigating factor that ought to reflect in the sentence imposed. To this end, there ought to be a difference in the sentence imposed on an offender who has pleaded guilty and one who has claimed trial.

87     In the present case, the Accused, having claimed trial, was not entitled to any sentencing discount. Having regard to this and the belligerence the Accused had demonstrated in refusing to provide his urine specimen, I agreed with the Prosecution that an uplift from the mandatory minimum sentence (which would otherwise have been imposed on an offender who had pleaded guilty) was necessary. I thus sentenced the Accused to 7 years and 3 months' imprisonment. Given the length of his incarceration, I did not impose any imprisonment in lieu of caning.

88     The Accused is currently serving sentence.
